<br>
And no, having your IP is not all someone needs.  They need to know of a backdoor on your computer and know how to exploit it.  Finding your IP is the easy part.  Whenever you go to a public website, they have your IP address.  Nothing you can really do about that short of setting up a firewall, and there is no reason to either.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=modauth>modauth</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 118<br> <font color=#333333>(11/18/02 4:42:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7894.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: .</span><hr size=1> Firewall or no firewall it doesn't matter. The very second you plug your connection into the outside you are now officially at risk. The only &quot;sure&quot; way to ensure your security is to well, unplug the cat v line. In fact they may have not specifically even targeted you. Most potential attackers will not scan just one ip, they set a scanner to scan an entire block of ip addresses. Say for example <br>
<br>
start 1.1.0.254 - 1.254.254.254 <br>
<br>
Now that is a LOAD of potential targets. What happens is you leave it running and go do laundry, drink beer, watch tv, play eq even. Come back to a text file that's been output with potential targets and ones that are no good. Basically saying &quot; these hosts have possible vulnerabilities on these services&quot;. These are saved and investigated more thoroughly at the attackers discretion as a process of elimination so that they can single out the systems they have a fairly good chance of accessing. These are individually attacked to detect known vulnerabilties. Hacks such as these are 'script kiddy' hacks. Why? because you know that you've been compromised. Either being an eq account or your entire OS. If I were you, I would backup important personal files and format, then reinstall as soon as possible. <br>
